Boil a full #kettle.

Meanwhile, trim and discard the root and dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways, then thinly slice.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @lemon{1/2}.

Pour the @boiled water for the risotto{750%ml} into a large #measuring jug{}. Stir in the @vegetable stock paste{20%g} - this is your stock.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil for the crumb{1%tbsp} in a large, wide-bottomed #saucepan on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the leek, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @Cajun spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and cook for ~{1%minute}, then stir in the @risotto rice{175%g}, stir and cook until the edges of the rice are translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Pour in a third of the stock and stir to combine. Bring to the boil and simmer until absorbed, then repeat with the remaining stock, a third at a time. Stir occasionally.

> The total cooking time should take 20-25 mins and your risotto is done when the rice is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

Once the risotto has 5 mins cook time remaining, drain the @king prawns{300%g}.

Stir the prawns into the risotto and simmer for ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Remove the risotto from the heat, then stir through the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and a knob of @?butter{} until melted.

Stir vigorously until well combined, then finish with a squeeze of lemon juice.

Taste and season with salt, pepper and more lemon juice if needed.

Share the prawn risotto between your #bowls{}.

Scatter over the @crispy onions{1%sachet} to finish.

Enjoy!